b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Man accessed 7,000 robots with gamepad"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"DJI pays $30,000 bug bounty"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Security flaw exposed home camera feeds"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["A man attempting to control his DJI robot vacuum with a PlayStation gamepad accidentally discovered he could access approximately 7,000 other devices—complete with camera feeds into strangers' homes. DJI has confirmed it will pay $30,000 for the discovery, turning an unsettling security nightmare into a lucrative bug bounty. The Valentine's Day incident, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com","children":"first reported by The Verge"}],", exposes the fragile security architecture underlying connected home robotics.\nThis wasn't sophisticated hacking. The researcher simply wanted to steer his own device using alternative input methods. What he found was an exposed network infrastructure that apparently required no authentication to access other users' robots. According to available information, the vulnerability would have allowed remote viewing through onboard cameras—a privacy breach of staggering scale. The gap between what these devices promise and how they're secured remains embarrassingly wide."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/accidental-hacker-gets-30k-for-7-000-robot-securit/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The $30,000 Question Behind 7,000 Exposed Robots","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"The $30,000 Question Behind 7,000 Exposed Robots"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The real question isn't how this happened, but how many similar vulnerabilities exist across the consumer robotics landscape. Connected devices with cameras, microphones, and internet connectivity ship with default configurations that prioritize ease-of-setup over security. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com/tech","children":"DJI has faced scrutiny before"}]," over data practices, making this latest incident part of a troubling pattern.\nFrom a hardware perspective, the attack surface here is significant. Each robot carries sensors, cameras, and network connectivity—yet the security model apparently assumed benign users would never probe beyond their own device. The $30,000 bounty represents a relatively low cost for DJI compared to what a malicious actor might have extracted from 7,000 compromised home surveillance nodes. As ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com/robotics","children":"consumer robotics companies race to add features"}],", security architecture appears to be trailing behind marketing velocity. The deployment reality is that these devices enter homes with minimal oversight and even less transparency about their network exposure."]}]]}]
